WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.580
Perception is influenced by
the perceptual set, context,

00:00:04.580 --> 00:00:07.790
motivation, and emotion.

00:00:07.790 --> 00:00:10.750


00:00:10.750 --> 00:00:14.730
Perceptual set, or perceptual expectancy,
is the tendency to perceive things based

00:00:14.730 --> 00:00:16.370
on past experiences or expectations.

00:00:16.370 --> 00:00:19.250
For example, preschool
children believe

00:00:19.250 --> 00:00:22.240
burgers taste better when
served in a McDonald's bag

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:24.820
than in a plain white bag.

00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:29.020
Perception is also influenced
by stereotypes about culture,

00:00:29.020 --> 00:00:34.450
ethnicity, gender identity,
sexual orientation, income, age,

00:00:34.450 --> 00:00:38.460
and ability levels
in everyday life.

00:00:38.460 --> 00:00:41.890
Context plays a role
in shaping perceptions.

00:00:41.890 --> 00:00:44.750
For example, drivers
tend to dislike

00:00:44.750 --> 00:00:47.850
pedestrians' leisurely
pace, while pedestrians tend

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:51.010
to dislike drivers' impatience.

00:00:51.010 --> 00:00:53.200
Motivation affects perception.

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:56.830
For example, climbing a
mountain with a heavy backpack

00:00:56.830 --> 00:00:59.770
feels harder if the climber has less
motivation to get to the top.

00:00:59.770 --> 00:01:01.090


00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:04.599
But, a motivation to
watch a beautiful sunset

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:07.960
from the mountain top makes
one move faster ignoring

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:09.910
the discomfort.

00:01:09.910 --> 00:01:12.490
Emotions, too, can
drive perceptions

00:01:12.490 --> 00:01:14.200
in different directions.

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:18.170
For instance, hearing sad
music can lead to interpreting

00:01:18.170 --> 00:01:20.480
homophonic words with
a sadder meaning,

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:24.430
such as hearing "mourning"

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:25.000
instead of "morning."

